sect2.para:
CCCConfer (
http://www.cccconfer.org/index1.aspx
) provides Synchronous conferencing services for the 108 campuses of the California Community College system. The service initially used Wimba products but now has changed to Elluminate Live.

Etudes NG should be singled out and analyzed in more detail. Originally a project developed by an Instructor at Foothill College as an alternative to the big commercial Learning Management Systems; Etudes morphed into a Sakai derivative driven by a Consortium (
http://www.etudesproject.org/
) with a current membership of 23 community colleges.

sect1.para:
Moodle (
http://www.moodle.org
) has always been an interesting alternative in the LMS competition, dominated by WebCT and Blackboard until the later acquired WebCT in 2006. With recent changes in the system wide procurement of LMS software people are starting to look at Moodle as a viable alternative to the big commercial LMS vendors in an Open Source Format.

Moodle has also spawned several for-profit commercial groups that provide services beyond those the Moodle community can offer. One of these commercial support companies is Moodlerooms (
http://www.moodlerooms.com/
) whose western regional office is headed by a former Humboldt State University staff member. According to their website, Moodlerooms offers the following services to the Moodle community:

listitem.para:
Customization Services: Ever dreamed of a new feature? With open-source code and a development team, Moodlerooms can shape Moodle to better match your needs and vision. (
Moodlerooms
)

glossdef.para:
The scope for IMS specifications, broadly defined as "distributed learning," includes both online and off-line settings, taking place synchronously (real-time) or asynchronously. This means that the learning contexts benefitting from IMS specifications include Internet-specific environments (such as web-based course management systems) as well as learning situations that involve off-line electronic resources (such as a learner accessing learning resources on a CD-ROM). The learners may be in a traditional educational environment (school classroom, university), in a corporate or government training setting, or at home. For example, the IMS Learning Resources Meta-data Specification (
http://www.imsglobal.org/metadata
), benefits the learner looking for information with a meta-data aware search tool both when the search is of web-based resources and when she or he is searching through a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM encyclopedia in their computer at home. Content developers who have implemented the IMS Learning Resources Meta-data Specification will have made it much easier for the people doing the search to find the resources they want in a much more efficient way, since meta-data allows users to be much more specific in the search terms they can specify.
